description._content: Here we are again! I first tried to take this photograph back in 2008, but discovered (as is so often the case) that the shot that had looked so good on the back of the camera did not live up to expectations on the computer. The main culprit was the wind, which had caused sufficient shake in the tripod to cause the shot to suffer from blur. For those interested, it can be found here. Not living locally, I wasn't able to go back and have another go. Jump to January this year, and when I found myself driving by the Marin Headlands shortly before dusk, it seemed silly not to try the photo again! I'm much happier with the image quality this time round, and the Christmas lights at the Embarcadero Center (incidentally where this photo was taken) are just an added bonus! Annoyingly, taking this shot has got a little harder since 2008. Concerns about landslides caused Conzelman Road to be re-engineered in 2010, with the result that it's no longer possible to pull over at this spot, as the road is relatively narrow and with metal barriers at the sides. This means that it's necessary to park up and walk here. There is still room to set up a tripod between the barriers and the cliff edge. If you're trying this, take care, especially around the cliff edge and when walking back in the dark! It's also worth mentioning that due to parallax, the spot to get this alignment is very small -- a movement 10cm to the left or right is enough to ruin the effect, so get there early!

photo.title: Happy Holidays from the Bay Bridge

description._content: Update: I don't normally do this but after failing to have The Beacon lit on our first attempt, we went back about a week later and were more successful! I placed the now lit Beacon onto the original photo and have replaced the one I uploaded to flickr with the new version (since I don't believe in "reposting"). I've updated the EXIF time so that you can all see the new version, if you like. Willie and I have been wanting to take the (now popular) San Francisco skyline photo from under the Bay Bridge for a while now. The photo is much much nicer during the holiday time when 17,000 lights outlining the Embarcadero Center buildings are turned on and a bright white light (called The Beacon) is turned on at the Transamerica Building (the triangular building). Willie had been checking the SF webcams and it looked like The Beacon was being lit each night. Last year it had been lit by this time of year so we thought we should be pretty safe in making sure The Beacon would be lit. We left work early and headed out to Treasure Island with plenty of time to find parking, hike up the hill, find "the spot" and then get setup. Unfortunately when US-101 and I-280 merged we hit a HUGE Friday afternoon holiday traffic. We arrived at Treasure Island much much later than planned (almost an hour later), and had to high tail it up the hill and over the Bay Bridge (we were both sweating pretty badly). After hopping the guard rail we actually found the spot pretty easily (just as we were walking over the Bridge a CalTrans truck drove by and screamed over the loud speaker "No photographs from this side of the bridge." We kept walking). We scouted out the area for a while, found our spots and then waited for the light to get nice. When I originally composed this image I wanted to make the SF Cityscape as large as possible, which meant that I clipped off some of the lights on the Bay Bridge. Once it got dark enough I realized that I really did want to include the extra light on the Bridge and I had zoom out and recomposed to get this final composition. Luckily for us there was an absolutely BEAUTIFUL sunset that night, which makes the photo much more interesting. Unfortunately though, as the sun began to set we noticed that the Transamerica Beacon was NOT going to turn on :(. The city lights started to come on, then the 17,000 Embarcadero Center lights were visible but The Beacon stayed a flashing red light. No luck for us. This meant that Willie and I would have to come back at another time, hoping the Beacon would be lit. Our second attempt was made 6 days later, after we both confirmed that The Beacon was lit at 5pm the previous couple of nights. The Beacon was the first light we could see on our 2nd attempt! Unfortunately on the 2nd night the sky was extremely boring and the photo didn't turn out as well as the previous week. I decided to composite the 2 trips and put the lit Beacon on top of the original photo. I hope you enjoy. photo.title: New Lens!

description._content:
365 Project Day 334: November 30, 2011

Out seeing what the new lens can do on Kite Hill tonight.  I found a good deal on a 70-300mm lens, an have, at times, wanted a longer lens, so I went for it.  I happened to be near Kite Hill tonight with my tripod, so I stopped to test it out.  So far, I like having the option to get closer in situations like this, where I can't physically move closer.  That said, I don't think I'll be able to use it for night shots in even the slightest breeze.  Any small shake from the wind is amplified way more than I expected, even with my heavy tripod.  For the most part, I don't think I'll carry it regularly, since it isn't really my style.  I like to be close, and would probably use a wider lens more often, but the price was right, and I'm sure I can find some interesting uses for this range.

All in all, it seems to be a nice lens, and works pretty well, despite my hunch that the FedEx carrier tossed it over my front gate...

photo.title: The White Light Calls To Us

description._content:
365 Project Day 333: November 29, 2011

The white light was on atop the pyramid tonight, and that same low fog from yesterday was back.  I could see Sutro Tower from the freeway, so my first plan was to head up to Twin Peaks to check out the view.  Unfortunately, all the fog in the world chose to gather up there tonight, and I couldn't see 6 feet in front of my car.  So, I headed down the hill and noticed that Tank Hill was clear.  I've taken enough city skylines and shots from Tank Hill that I wanted something at least a little different.  Luckily, I stumbled upon this guy hanging out and taking in the view.

I'm having a lot of trouble with the sky on this one.  I don't notice it in lightroom, but once I export, I'm seeing a lot of posterization.  The original was a little noisy, so I upped the noise reduction, but for all the other values, adjustments were pretty minor.  It seems that trying to drop the clarity of the sky to get blur this a bit just makes it worse.  I'm still seeing it if I drop the noise reduction back down, albeit to a lesser extent.  Maybe I've just been staring at it too long, but I'd be interested if anyone has a method to correct this.  I'll have to revisit later.

photo.title: Pyramid's Last Light

description._content: www.silentgphotography.com Shot 7 of 31 in my Black and White October Project Take it or leave it...this is one of my favorite images I've posted. Minimal black and whites are obviously becoming a favorite discipline and I've always wanted to try a shot like this. I absolutely love going up to San Francisco and hitting the Presidio and Marin Headlands, etc. but next time I'm going to be concentrating on these types of photos...I think SLO might have a 4 story building somewhere.. Lightroom 3 only for just a couple minutes This shot was actually part of a series of long exposures I had planned on making an HDR with...but I scrapped that idea and thought a dark and ominous perspective of the Transamerica Pyramid would be a better change of pace from the hundreds of HDRs I've posted. 6 Seconds at f18 so some of the only light in the original RAW was the last bit of sunlight hitting the top of the Pyramid. photo.title: San Francisco - Financial District: Transamerica Pyramid

description._content:
The Transamerica Pyramid, at 600 Montgomery Street, was built by architect William Pereira for the Transamerica Corporation from 1969-1972.  At 853-feet above sea level, it is the tallest and most recognizable skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline.  At the time of its completion, it was the tallest building in the United States west of the Mississippi River, surpassed in 1974 by the Aon Center in Los Angeles.  Although the building no longer houses the Transamerica Corporation, it is still strongly associated with the company and depicted in their logo.

The building is a tall, four-sided 48-storey pyramid with two flared wings, topped with capped with a hollow, pointed spire that rises another 212-feet.  The wings rise vertically from the middle of the ground floor and extend beyond the frame, which tapers inward, starting at the 29th floor.  The unique shape casts a smaller shadow than conventional design.  The east wing houses 18 elevator shafts and the west wing houses a smoke tower and stairs.  The spire, covered with vertically louvred aluminum panels and lit from the inside at night, is purely decorative.  The exterior is covered with white precast quartz aggregate, interlaced with reinforcing rods on each floor.  Clearance between the panels allows lateral movement in the event of an earthquake.  The base is supported with a web of diagonal truses.  The foundation rests on a steel and concrete block, sunk 52-feet into the ground, designed to move with earth tremors.  During the 1989 earthquake, the top floor swayed nearly a foot from side to side.

In 2007, the Transamerica Pyramid was ranked #61 on the AIA 150 America's Favorite Architecture list.

photo.title: Not So Beat Anymore

description._content:
Looking down Columbus Street toward the TransAmerica Building on an early winter's day.  Definitely a scene where old San Francisco abruptly meets the new. City Lights Bookstore is immediately on the right followed by Vesuvio's bar. Both of these landmarks were frequented by the Beatniks during the 1950's "Beat Era." In fact, the alleyway that separates these two venerable establishments is named after Jack Keroauc. There's no doubt that it would have troubled Jack greatly if he knew that damn pyramid would someday tower over the block where he spent so many blissfully drunken moments...hic.

San Francisco, CA

photo.title: The Pyramid

description._content: The Transamerica Pyramid is the tallest skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline and one of its most iconic. Although the building no longer houses the headquarters of the Transamerica Corporation, it is still strongly associated with the company and is depicted in the company's logo. Designed by architect William Pereira and built by Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction Company, at 260 m (850 ft), upon completion in 1972 it was among the five tallest buildings in the world. The tower has no public access except for the first floor lobby, so visitors can't reach the top for a panoramic view. Wikipedia Joke on board the hop-on hop-off bus tour, "Without the Transamerica Pyramid, the San Francisco skyline would have no point." Please hit L and view larger.

The "Bay Bridge" traverses the Bay between the two cities (the Golden Gate Bridge is not viewable from this location). Along this side of the shore, the cranes for loading cargo on ships can be seen at the Oakland port. I've also added notes to identify some of the more prominent buildings. photo.title: The Gateway

description._content: Golden Gate Bridge San Francisco, California My Facebook Blog Well, we rolled into San Francisco at roughly one in the afternoon or so. My wife and I have never been there, and I was worried about getting around the city and finding shots that have portrayed the city so well. One of the shots I wanted, although I have seen it numerous times, was this one with the Transamerica Pyramid sticking through the opening on one of the bridge towers. So our first agenda was to find this location. Quite honestly, I found the location easily. I also found driving around the city not difficult at all. I was even able to find some parking spots near some of the locations we went. Anyway, I got to this location and lined up the pyramid and waited for the sun to set. I was in awe as I stood along Conzelman Road staring at this beautiful sight in front of me. I could not believe I was standing here looking at the Golden Gate Bridge. It was not a perfectly clear evening, but the view was breathtaking nonetheless. I also learned that as many shots as I have seen of the Golden Gate Bridge, none of them were the same. None of the fog patterns are ever the same, none of light and colors are ever the same. Anyway, I hope you enjoy the image. I cannot wait to get back to San Francisco again... a city of endless photo opportunities.

photo.title: Concrete Skyline

description._content: San Francisco, California My Facebook Blog Each morning I traveled around the city in our rental car looking for opportunities for sunrises. One of the mornings while I was out I pulled out my iphone and searched flickr for shots tagged with 'San Francisco'. Upon doing so I found this location that I was previously unaware of. It is located at Texas and 19th on a hill overlooking the city. I really liked the overview of the highway leading into and out of the city. Unfortunately, this was a Friday night and even with a long exposure of 30 seconds, the stop and go traffic of the traffic leading into the city still allowed some tail lights to bleed through instead of a nice steady stream of red. I also wanted a shot from just a few minutes later where the sky was just a bit darker and the illumination from the windows stood out a bit more, but as the weather in San Francisco would have it, a rain storm came rolling in literally as soon as this shot was taken and stayed for about 15 minutes. Just long enough that the glow I was after was gone. I still felt fortunate though as the forecast was for an all day rain, and the day was actually a pretty nice day with just a few spurts of showers that came rolling through. I quickly learned on this trip the weather in San Francisco is difficult to predict and changes very rapidly. I will not pretend I know any of the buildings here except for the Transamerica Pyramid which is the spire sticking up just to the left of center. If anyone knows any of the buildings here feel free to let us know. Fun fact I just found out about... This shot was taken in front of the Pacific Heights house used in the movie starring Michael Keaton, Melanie Griffith and Matthew Modine.

photo.title: Jessie

description._content: I met up with a friend for coffee in the Financial District, then wandered into North Beach, where I considered taking a photo of the Transamerica Pyramid and Columbus Tower from the intersection of Columbus and Broadway. I tend to prefer the shady areas when shooting with the Rolleicord because its fastest shutter speed is 1/500th of a second and in sunlight, that means having to stop the lens down further than I want, especially when shooting portraits. The mid-afternoon light, however, was gorgeous as it fell on the sculpted trees (in the background), so I walked across the street a couple of times to see if there were any compositions that appealed to me. While looking through the camera, framing a potential shot, Jessie approached the street corner from my left and remarked, "That's an old one, isn't it?" "Yes," I said, "from the early '50s. It's older than I am! And... because you asked about the camera, I have to take your photograph." It is quite incredible to me that I have really yet to get any pushback when I utter those words. Jessie, in fact, seemed quite delighted to have her photo taken (as, actually, are most of my subjects), and I was fortunate that the crossing light had just turned red when she approached me, although I made mention of having to hurry before the light changed. Because of the bright sun, she squinted and blinked a bit, and I was afraid I caught her blinking. After the shot, we crossed the street, where we exchanged email addresses. I'm bummed that I have only been able to share a handful of these portraits, despite having given my card out to every person I've photographed, so it was nice to be able to send Jessie's to her as I'm quite pleased with it.

description._content: View Large Backlit aerial view of the Transamerica Pyramid and many of San Francisco's taller buildings. I was flying my helium balloon-cam from Chinatown's Portsmouth Square Park, just a block from the Transamerica Pyramid. For some reason I thought that the building, San Francisco's tallest, was in the 550 to 650 foot range. Looking it up, I now find that it's 850 feet tall. Impressive! The Bay Bridge and San Francisco Bay are seen in the upper left of the photograph. Thanks to Alan Grinberg for his company and assistance with the balloon-cam. photo.title: Beams of Light over San Francisco

description._content:
The lights hit the low-lying clouds creating a soft glow in the sky.   Taken on the night before Labor Day 2011.  The Ferry Building is to the right and the tip of the TransAmerica Pyramid can be seen to the left.

The light display may most likely be for something else, but these  two beams of light  remind me of the somber anniversary that happened on the Great City in the opposite side of the coast exactly 10 years ago from the day I uploaded this.   That was the day that America will never ever forget.

photo.title: The Eye of Sauron

description._content:
If you stand at the right spot the Presidio of San Francisco in mid to late July, you can see a surprisingly bright light appear at the top of the Transamerica Pyramid for about two minutes sometime between 12:40pm and 12:50pm.  The sun and the pyramid align to reflect the sunlight towards the Presidio.

This photo was shot on July 26, 2011 from the overlook on Lincoln Boulevard above Crissy Field (see map).
